aditional medical secrecy first came under pressure from demands of disclosure in the name of public health. Maehle structures his study around three representative questions of the time that remain salient today: Do physicians have a privilege to refuse court orders to reveal confidential patient details? Is there a medical duty to report illegal procedures to the authorities? Should doctors breach confidentiality in order to prevent the spread of disease? Considering these debates through a unique historical perspective, Contesting Medical Confidentiality illuminates the ethical issues and potentially grave consequences that continue to stir up public debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysiciansxHistoryy19th century. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysiciansxHistoryy20th century. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszGermanyxHistory. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPhysiciansxProfessional ethics. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxHistory. 4aBritain. 4aGermany. 4aUnited States. 4aabortion. 4amedical confidentiality. 4amedical privilege. 4amedical secrecy. 4apatient information. 4aprivacy. 4avenereal diseases. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226404967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226404967.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3